<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-406-918  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 406 918.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  May 1990 v15 n5 p311(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In any event. (event handling in graphical user interface systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grehan, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) use software driven by 'events'such as key presses or the use of mice and other input devices.andO;Common GUIs such as Windows, Presentation Manager, and theMacintosh funnel user-input events into a queue by capturinginterrupts in the system kernel.andP;  Event messages are pulled offthe queue by application programs, which examine them and executethe appropriate routine.andP;  The queue is a two-ended stack in whichthe system pushes events onto one end while the application pullsthem off the other.andP;  Multitasking systems maintain separate eventqueues for each task.andP;  Event-driven systems handle complex datastructures as objects.andP;  The Macintosh keeps its event manager atthe lowest level, but not all application programs need to callit.andP;  Windows offers greater multitasking support.andP;  Event handlingin Presentation Manager, DESQview, and X Windows is alsodescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceEvent-Driven SystemsProgrammingSystems SoftwareSoftware Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationprogram.andO;Caption:   C pseudocode for a simple event loop. (program)Event handling in a multiwindow environment - in this case,Windows. (program)A DESQview event loop. (program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>